{
  "texts": [
    "DPI involves tricking the agent directly through the textual input into performing unintended actions, which can result in sensitive information disclosure or unauthorized tool use, by the user.",
    "Furthermore, agents can also be manipulated by third-party attackers using a method known as indirect prompt injection (IPI) (Greshake et al., 2023; Shayegani et al., 2023; Verma et al., 2024).",
    "Unlike DPI, IPI involves injecting malicious instructions into external information sources, which the agent then unknowingly processes using its tools.",
    "This attack vector is particularly concerning, as it does not require direct access to the agent and can potentially affect multiple agents that access the contaminated sources (Shayegani et al., 2023).",
    "The ease with which an attacker can insert harmful requests into various information sources, such as emails, websites, and online comments, makes IPI a significant threat."
  ]
}